that the inflationary creation of credit was key to Japan's postwar success—and its eventual demise due to its instability over the long term.To prove his case, Metzler explores heterodox ideas about economic life, in particular Joseph Schumpeter's realization that inflation is intrinsic to capitalist development. Schumpeter's ideas, widely ignored within standard American neoclassical economic theory, were shaped by his experience of Austria's reconstruction after 1918. They were highly influential in Japan, and Metzler traces their impact in the period from the Allied Occupation, starting in 1945, through the Income Doubling Plan of 1960. Japan after defeat, Metzler argues, illustrates the critical importance of inflationary credit creation for increased production.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCapitalxHistoryx20th centuryxJapan. 0aCapitalzJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aCapitalismxHistoryx20th centuryxJapan. 0aCapitalismzJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aCreditxHistoryx20th centuryxJapan. 0aCreditzJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aSaving and investmentxHistoryx20th centuryxJapan. 0aSaving and investmentzJapanxHistoryy20th century. 4aAsian Studies. 4aGeneral Economics. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Japan.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146791240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801467912423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801467912/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aE